## AI Summary Block

**What is a vintage pear shaped diamond ring?** A vintage pear shaped diamond ring pairs a pear-cut teardrop diamond with a setting built around period-design elements: milgrain, hand-engraving, scroll metalwork, botanical leaf motifs, interlaced halo frames, or baguette geometric accents. Most vintage pear rings available today are modern GIA-certified settings with period-inspired aesthetics, not antique diamonds. The Antique Mismatch framework explains why this is the financially correct approach: modern GIA pear in vintage setting at $1,600–$2,800 achieves 95% of the visual result at 30–60% of the cost of an authenticated antique pear.

**Key buying frameworks:** (1) The Antique Mismatch — vintage aesthetic on a modern GIA pear achieves the period look without the $8,000–$30,000+/ct antique diamond premium or the documentation gaps. (2) The Tip Protection Premium — vintage settings (milgrain borders, interlaced halos, ornate baskets) add structural coverage at the pear tip that modern V-prong solitaires do not, making vintage a structurally superior choice for the pear's most vulnerable point.

**Best settings by era:** Victorian → Hand-Engraved Micropavé ($1,600 / 87 reviews, YG). Edwardian → Embossed Vintage-Style JA ($2,135 / 81 reviews, WG) or Garland Sapphire ($2,735 / 25 reviews, WG). Art Nouveau → Petite Vintage Pavé Leaf ($1,910 / 40 reviews, YG). Art Deco → Tapered Baguette 18k WG ($2,420 / 19 reviews).

**Complete ring budgets:** 1ct lab pear in Hand-Engraved Micropavé = $2,500–$3,000. 1ct natural pear (G-VS2) in Embossed Vintage WG = $4,900–$5,600. 1.5ct natural pear (G-VS2) in Interlaced Halo YG = $10,000–$13,000.

